{
  "texts": [
    "Some in society, such as absolute pacifists would expect soldiers to always suffer moral injury in a conflict because they believe that the act of killing is unethical under any circumstances.",
    "This chapter assumes a just war perspective that acts of harm by a state are, in some cases, justified.",
    "In those cases, the military ought to ensure soldiers are fully cognisant of why war is being waged and why it believes that the conduct expected of soldiers is justified.",
    "A soldier's individual sense of ethical conduct is constructed within these institutional conditions.",
    "Moral injury can be caused by ethical discordance between the individual regarding whether entering a conflict itself is just (jus ad bellum), how soldiers judge their own conduct during a conflict, but also how soldiers perceive the ethical conduct of the military they serve during a conflict (jus in bello)."
  ]
}